s, and elaborates the theory he first proposed in Rhetorical Power, and he exemplifies it with a new series of provocative reception histories. He also both critiques and reconceptualizes the version of reader response criticism he developed in his first book, Interpretive Conventions. Throughout Reception Histories, Mailloux demonstrates his distinctive blend of neopragmatism and cultural rhetoric study. By tracing the rhetorical paths of thought, this book offers a new way to read the current volatile debates over higher education and contributes its own original proposals for shaping the future of the humanities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCriticismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCulture conflictzUnited States. 0aEnglish languagezUnited StatesxRhetoric. 0aEnglish philologyxStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited States. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aMulticulturalismzUnited States. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited States. 0aPragmatism. 0aReader-response criticismzUnited States. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172843340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501728433423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501728433/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles